article.description:
Gary Payton scored 23 points and reserve center Predrag Drobnjak had six of his career-high 18 points during
a key fourth-quarter run as the Seattle SuperSonics beat the Los Angeles Clippers 95-87 Saturday night.
article.headline: Sonics' Drobnjak scores 18 in reserve role
article.linkText: Sonics hold on in West battle with Clippers
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Seattle SuperSonics took a big step toward shaking the Los Angeles Clippers from their rearview mirror and securing a berth in the playoffs.
Drobnjak

Gary Payton scored 23 points and reserve center Predrag Drobnjak had six of his career-high 18 points during a key fourth-quarter run as the Sonics withstood a late barrage of 3-pointers and hung on for a 95-87 victory Saturday night. The Clippers slipped three games behind seventh-place Seattle and two games behind Utah for the eighth Western Conference playoff berth. "All the games are big," Payton said. "We needed to come in here and not let them gain a game on us. We've had a lot of injuries and we've been struggling a little bit. This was a gut check for us, and these guys showed as much heart as they can show." Jeff McInnis scored 30 points and Eric Piatkowski added 20 for the Clippers, who have dropped 31 of their last 34 meetings with the Sonics. Using their 18th different starting lineup, the Sonics dressed only nine players because of injuries to Vin Baker, Earl Watson, Vladimir Radmanovic, Calvin Booth and Rashard Lewis. Lewis strained his left shoulder in Friday night's home loss to Washington and didn't make the trip. Even during the two stretches in which Payton was on the bench, his teammates outscored the Clippers 26-17. "We talked about everyone doing their part at the beginning of the game," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "I think some of the role players, when they get additional minutes, start to feel comfortable out there on the floor. And we beat a very good team tonight." The Clippers, already without Lamar Odom, Corey Maggette and Keyon Dooling, lost sixth man Quentin Richardson late in the first half because of a deep thigh bruise. The injuries could doom one of the NBA's most improved teams. "It's a big setback," said Clippers forward Elton Brand, who had 14 rebounds and eight points. "We needed to really put them behind the 8-ball, but they put us behind it. If Seattle is playing like this with all their injuries, they're going to be tough to catch." The Sonics, who entered with a league-leading 46.6 field-goal percentage, opened the fourth quarter with an 8-0 run fueled by six points from Drobnjak for a 76-63 lead with 9:36 to play. "We didn't step up defensively and they did," Brand said. "Drobnjak came off the bench and provided a great spark for them. They seemed like they were the team that needed to win this game. They were very aggressive on every loose ball." McInnis made four 3-pointers in the final 4:08, rallying the Clippers within 91-87 with 37.5 seconds left. But Payton, whose 43 points against the Clippers on Dec. 27 in Seattle were the most this season by a Sonics player, clinched it with four free throws. "This is a huge win for us," Desmond Mason said. "To be on the road and win is huge. This helps us get back on track and get more of a cushion going into the playoffs." The Clippers trailed by seven points early in the third quarter before Piatkowski's 3-pointer capped a 7-0 spurt and tied the score at 51 with 8:44 left in the period. But Seattle pulled ahead 68-63 by the end of the period. Payton and Drobnjak paced the Sonics to a 45-41 halftime lead with 10 points each. They erased an early nine-point deficit, using a 12-0 run to pull ahead 45-39 with four seconds left in the half. Piatkowski got two of the points back at the buzzer, guiding in a high-arching 27-footer by McInnis that was short. Game notes
The Clippers held an opponent under 100 points for the 10th straight time, tying the franchise record set Nov. 12-29 of last season. ... Earl Boykins, the Clippers' 5-foot-5 reserve guard, was walking down the sideline to midcourt with one of the ballboys in the final seconds of the third quarter when referee Joe Crawford shouted to coach Alvin Gentry: "Which one's coming in?" ... The Sonics, whose road loss to the Clippers on Dec. 12 made them 0-8 in the second half of back-to-back games, are 8-2 in those situations since then. ... Payton had four steals and needs five more to become the ninth player in NBA history with 2,000.
